## TForge AI Contributor

- **Scope**
  - Focus on code quality (Go + frontend), security/secrets (especially `internal/secure/*`), and developer experience (CLI, agent, Wails app).
  - Use the language configured for the agent/system when talking to users; keep rules and code comments in English.
  - Do not change license/ownership/legal text without explicit instruction.

- **Git, Commits, Branches**
  - Never change Git config or hooks.
  - Only create commits when the user explicitly asks for it; do not auto-commit
    just because work has been completed.
  - Commit titles: short, descriptive, in English; link issues with `Fixes #<n>` / `Closes #<n>` when appropriate.
  - Never push unless explicitly requested.
  - When an AI agent contributes to a change, include it (and any other agents)
    as **co-authors** using standard Git trailers in the commit body:
    `Co-authored-by: Name <email>`. The `<email>` should be a GitHub-associated
    (or GitHub noreply) address so that GitHub recognises these co-authors
    on commits and pull requests.

- **Issues, Milestones, Roadmap**
  - When an issue is mentioned, close it via commit message only if the change truly fixes it.
  - Keep README/Roadmap items (checkboxes, strikethroughs) in sync with implemented work when asked.
  - Use `gh` for PRs, labels, milestones only on explicit request.

- **Coding Standards**
  - Respect `go.mod` (Go version and dependencies); prefer reusing existing structure before adding new deps.
  - Treat `internal/secure/*` as security‑sensitive: no logging of secrets or key material; migrations must keep backups, be documented, and avoid silent data loss.
  - For frontend/Wails, keep UI modern and readable, but avoid unnecessary experiments; respect existing build pipelines.

- **Tooling**
  - After substantial edits, run `go build ./...` (and `go test ./...` when relevant) and check lints for new issues.
  - Use `gh` only for user‑requested GitHub operations; never modify repo settings.

- **Security & Communication**
  - Never invent real secrets/tokens/keys; use clearly fake values in examples.
  - No automatic exports/backups of `vaults.bin`/`master.key` outside explicitly requested flows.
  - Communicate concisely and technically, always summarising what changed and why, and make assumptions explicit when requirements are ambiguous.

